I think this is correct. The table you&#39;re describing is what&#39;s called a join table, which through its records links `User`s and `Project`s together. You can read this as &#39;User 1 has project 2&#39;, &#39;User 3 has Project 5&#39; etc. This table doesn&#39;t store any other data, it just serves to link the two models. I think you can query it with `user.getProjects()` as per the Sequelize docs.

If you need a table with the ID as a property (and maybe some others you define), you need to define a model yourself. Then, you do

    User.associate(models =&gt; {
    	User.belongsToMany(models.Project, {
    		through: &#39;UserProject&#39;
    	});
    });
    
    Project.associate(models =&gt; {
    	Project.belongsToMany(models.User, {
    		through: &#39;UserProject&#39;
    	});
    });
    
    UserProject.associate(models =&gt; {
    	UserProject.belongsTo(models.User, {
    		through: &#39;UserProject&#39;
    	});
    	UserProject.belongsTo(models.Project, {
    		through: &#39;UserProject&#39;
    	});
    });

This is basically creating the association manually. This allows you to store other properties as well, which you can define in the `UserProject` model.
